arth in Rochdale (Lancashire), possibly from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’. The name may have been confused with   Haworth  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Chaworth was born in 1167, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Chaworth, was 40 and his mother, Agnes, was 20. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Alice de Alfreton. He died in 1232, in his hometown, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1167–1232":"1167–1232","1170–1225":"1170–1225","1190–1263":"1190–1263","1191–Male":"1191–Surnud","1198–1260":"1198–1260","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1148–Female":"1148–Surnud","1190":"1190","1127":"1127","1225":"1225","1148":"1148","abt 1191":"umbes 1191","1167":"1167","1232":"1232","1198":"1198","1263":"1263","1260":"1260","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Of, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Alfreton, Derby, Eng":"Alfreton, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Watnall, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Watnall Chaworth, Greasley, Nottinghamshire, England":"Watnall Chaworth, Nottinghamshire, England","Beauchief Abbey, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Beauchief, Derbyshire, Inglis